# AiWroteMeRules - Coding Style and Development Guidelines

## Code Formatting and Style
- **Tooling**: Use Prettier + ESLint combination for code formatting and style consistency
- **Indentation**: 2 spaces for indentation across all languages
- **Semicolons**: Use default practices (typically always use semicolons)
- **Quotes**: Use default practices (typically single quotes for strings)
- **Trailing Commas**: Use default practices (typically always use trailing commas in multiline structures)

## Import Organization
- **Structure**: Keep all imports at the top of files with no specific grouping
- **Style**: Use named imports over default imports when possible
- **Optimization**: Import only what you need (tree-shaking friendly)

## Naming Conventions
- **Variables and Functions**: camelCase (myVariable, myFunction)
- **Constants**: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (MY_CONSTANT)
- **React Components**: PascalCase (MyComponent)
- **CSS Classes and IDs**: kebab-case (my-class)

## File and Directory Structure
- **Component Files**: One component per file, files named same as component
- **File Naming**: PascalCase for React components (MyComponent.tsx)
- **Directory Naming**: kebab-case (my-feature/)

## TypeScript Preferences
- **Settings**: Use moderate TypeScript settings
- **Type Definitions**: Explicit typing everywhere (let name: string = "hello")
- **Type Patterns**: Interface over type aliases
- **Error Handling**: Try-catch blocks

## React and Component Patterns
- **State Management**: Use state management library (Redux, Zustand, etc.)
- **Components**: Functional components with hooks
- **Props**: Default props with default parameters
- **Event Handling**: Mix based on complexity (inline for simple, separate functions for complex)

## Testing Preferences
- **Coverage**: Write tests for all components and functions
- **Framework**: Jest + React Testing Library
- **Organization**: Tests in separate __tests__ directories
- **Naming**: describe/it pattern (describe('Component', () => { it('should...') }))

## Performance and Optimization
- **Strategy**: Use optimization techniques selectively based on component complexity
- **Bundle Optimization**: All techniques (code splitting at route/component level, lazy loading)
- **Image Optimization**: Use optimized image formats (WebP, AVIF)

## Error Handling and Logging
- **Approach**: Comprehensive error boundaries and logging
- **Error Boundaries**: Mix of global and component-level error boundaries
- **Logging**: Console logging for development, external service for production

## Documentation and Comments
- **Functions/Components**: JSDoc comments for all functions and components
- **Component Documentation**: TypeScript interfaces with comments
- **Code Comments**: Comment complex algorithms and business logic

## Git and Version Control
- **Workflow**: Direct commits to main with good commit messages
- **Commit Messages**: Conventional commits (feat:, fix:, docs:, etc.)
- **Branch Naming**: feature/description (feature/user-authentication)

## Build and Deployment
- **Process**: Automated CI/CD with multiple environments
- **Environment Management**: Environment-specific configuration files
- **Build Optimization**: Production builds with minification and optimization

## Code Quality and Linting
- **Linting Rules**: Moderate linting rules, allow some warnings
- **Code Review**: Automated checks (linting, tests, type checking)
- **Formatting**: Auto-format on save

## Additional Guidelines
- **Code Readability**: Prioritize clean, readable code over micro-optimizations
- **Consistency**: Maintain consistent patterns throughout the codebase
- **Documentation**: Keep documentation up-to-date with code changes
- **Testing**: Ensure all tests pass before committing
- **Performance**: Profile and optimize only when performance issues are identified

## Tools and Extensions Recommended
- Prettier extension for VS Code
- ESLint extension for VS Code
- TypeScript extension for VS Code
- Jest extension for VS Code
- GitLens for Git integration
- Auto-format on save enabled

